us to go from thinking
to doing to being.

00:19:41.080 --> 00:19:44.950 align:middle line:10%
Each brain is its own
individual biocomputer

00:19:44.950 --> 00:19:48.700 align:middle line:10%
with its own anatomy and own
circuitry, its own physiology

00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:49.960 align:middle line:10%
and chemistry.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:52.720 align:middle line:84%
They even have their
own history, as well as

00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:55.920 align:middle line:84%
their own sense
of time and space.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:19:59.370 align:middle line:84%
Now, the first
brain, the neocortex,

00:19:59.370 --> 00:20:01.410 align:middle line:84%
it's the newest
brain in evolution.

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:03.850 align:middle line:84%
It's that walnut
shaped structure

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:05.760 align:middle line:84%
that sits on the
outside with all

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:08.710 align:middle line:84%
of its folds and
valleys in yellow there.

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:10.850 align:middle line:84%
It's the newest,
the most evolved

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:13.550 align:middle line:84%
and highly specialized
in human beings.

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:17.100 align:middle line:84%
Right under the neocortex
is called the limbic brain,

00:20:17.100 --> 00:20:19.480 align:middle line:84%
the chemical brain,
the emotional brain,

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:20.860 align:middle line:90%
or the mammalian brain.

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:23.100 align:middle line:84%
It's about the size
of a lemon, and it's

00:20:23.100 --> 00:20:27.152 align:middle line:84%
responsible for regulating
internal chemical order.

00:20:27.152 --> 00:20:28.610 align:middle line:84%
Right in the back
of the brain stem

00:20:28.610 --> 00:20:31.660 align:middle line:84%
there in red is
called the cerebellum.

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:33.410 align:middle line:90%
The reptilian brain.

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:35.540 align:middle line:84%
It's the oldest
brain in evolution.

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:38.510 align:middle line:84%
It's the seat of the
subconscious mind.

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:43.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, your brain is made up
of about 100 billion neurons.

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:45.250 align:middle line:84%
If you take 100
billion sheets of paper

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:46.980 align:middle line:84%
and stacked them on
top of each other,

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:49.670 align:middle line:90%
it would be 5,000 miles high.

00:20:49.670 --> 00:20:53.050 align:middle line:84%
That's the distance from
Los Angeles to London.

00:20:53.050 --> 00:20:56.240 align:middle line:84%
Now, nerve cells possess
the unique ability

00:20:56.240 --> 00:21:00.290 align:middle line:84%
to store and communicate
information between each other.

00:21:00.290 --> 00:21:02.880 align:middle line:84%
So your neocortex,
your thinking brain,

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:05.920 align:middle line:84%
is the seat of your
conscious awareness.

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:09.330 align:middle line:84%
You're listening to me right
now with your neocortex.

00:21:09.330 --> 00:21:13.880 align:middle line:84%
And what the neocortex loves
to do is to gather information.

00:21:13.880 --> 00:21:16.670 align:middle line:84%
And every time you
learn something new,

00:21:16.670 --> 00:21:18.860 align:middle line:84%
you make a new
synaptic connection

00:21:18.860 --> 00:21:20.100 align:middle line:90%
in your thinking brain.

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:21.380 align:middle line:90%
That's what learning is.

00:21:21.380 --> 00:21:24.240 align:middle line:84%
Learning is forging
new connections.

00:21:24.240 --> 00:21:26.490 align:middle line:84%
And every time you
learn something new,

00:21:26.490 --> 00:21:29.550 align:middle line:90%
your brain physically changes.

00:21:29.550 --> 00:21:32.200 align:middle line:84%
So you read a book on
how to ride a bicycle,

00:21:32.200 --> 00:21:34.970 align:middle line:84%
you read a book on how
to build a doghouse,

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:37.340 align:middle line:84%
read a book on how
to dance this salsa,

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:40.290 align:middle line:84%
how to cook French cuisine,
how to become successful,

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:44.060 align:middle line:84%
how to be a better parent,
and your brain literally

00:21:44.060 --> 00:21:48.450 align:middle line:84%
upscales its hardware to
reflect the new level of mind.

00:21:48.450 --> 00:21:52.200 align:middle line:84%
The principle in neuroscience
says this-- nerve cells

00:21:52.200 --> 00:21:55.140 align:middle line:84%
that fire together
wire together.

00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:58.060 align:middle line:84%
And as you begin to
learn new information,

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:00.760 align:middle line:84%
you biologically
wire that information

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:02.980 align:middle line:90%
into your cerebral architecture.

00:22:02.980 --> 00:22:05.990 align:middle line:84%
So if learning is making
new synaptic connections,

00:22:05.990 --> 00:22:08.900 align:middle line:84%
then remembering is
maintaining and sustaining

00:22:08.900 --> 00:22:10.640 align:middle line:90%
those connections.

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:15.030 align:middle line:84%
And just like any relationship,
the more you communicate,

00:22:15.030 --> 00:22:17.070 align:middle line:90%
the more bonded you become.

00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:20.690 align:middle line:84%
And neurons are
exactly the same way.

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:24.570 align:middle line:84%
Now, once these neurons begin
to fire and wire together,

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:27.560 align:middle line:84%
they actually form
networks, what

00:22:27.560 --> 00:22:30.560 align:middle line:84%
neuroscientists call
neural networks.

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:33.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, neural networks
are just gangs

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:36.320 align:middle line:84%
of neurons that have
fired and wired together

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:39.200 align:middle line:84%
to form a community of
neurosynaptic connections.

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:41.800 align:middle line:84%
It could be related
to an idea, a concept,

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:46.490 align:middle line:84%
of memory, experience, a
skill or behavior, an action.

00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:51.290 align:middle line:84%
But these networks actually have
an electrochemical component.

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:54.280 align:middle line:84%
And if you want to see
mind in action, watch this.

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:56.200 align:middle line:90%
That's a thought right there.

00:22:56.200 --> 00:23:00.250 align:middle line:84%
Again, so you generate
more electrical impulses

00:23:00.250 --> 00:23:03.070 align:middle line:84%
in your brain in one
day than all the cell

00:23:03.070 --> 00:23:06.270 align:middle line:84%
phones on the
planet put together.

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:09.100 align:middle line:84%
Now, the neuroscientific
definition of mind

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:11.420 align:middle line:90%
is mind is the brain in action.

00:23:11.420 --> 00:23:13.120 align:middle line:90%
Mind is the brain at work.

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:15.220 align:middle line:90%
Mind is what the brain does.

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:18.320 align:middle line:84%
And because we have 100 billion
neurons seamlessly pieced

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.210 align:middle line:84%
together, we can
make the brain fire

00:23:21.210 --> 00:23:23.920 align:middle line:84%
in different sequences,
different patterns,

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:25.850 align:middle line:90%
and different combinations.

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:28.400 align:middle line:10%
And whenever we make the
brain work differently,

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:31.070 align:middle line:10%
we're changing our mind.

00:23:31.070 --> 00:23:34.330 align:middle line:10%
So once you've understood
something intellectually,

00:23:34.330 --> 00:23:37.370 align:middle line:10%
theoretically, once you've
understood something

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:41.330 align:middle line:10%
philosophically, if you take
what you intellectually learned

00:23:41.330 --> 00:23:46.040 align:middle line:10%
in your thinking brain and you
apply it, you personalize it,

00:23:46.040 --> 00:23:47.810 align:middle line:10%
you demonstrate
it, it means you're

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:51.020 align:middle line:10%
going to have to modify
your behavior in some way.

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:53.620 align:middle line:84%
And if you change your
actions and you do something

00:23:53.620 --> 00:23:57.070 align:middle line:84%
differently, you're gonna
have a new experience.

00:23:57.070 --> 00:23:59.190 align:middle line:84%
Now, when you're in the
midst of an experience,

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:02.260 align:middle line:84%
everything you're seeing
and smelling and tasting

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:05.670 align:middle line:84%
and feeling and hearing,
all of your five senses

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:07.780 align:middle line:84%
are gathering this
vital information

00:24:07.780 --> 00:24:09.460 align:middle line:90%
from the environment.

00:24:09.460 --> 00:24:11.725 align:middle line:84%
And as you begin to process
all this information

00:24:11.725 --> 00:24:15.830 align:middle line:84%
and it's rushing back to your
brain, jungles of neurons

00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:19.050 align:middle line:84%
begin to organize
themselves into patterns.

00:24:19.050 --> 00:24:22.140 align:middle line:84%
The moment those neurons
string into place,

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:23.900 align:middle line:90%
the brain releases a chemical.

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:27.650 align:middle line:10%
And that chemical is called
a feeling or an emotion.

00:24:27.650 --> 00:24:31.410 align:middle line:10%
So experience, then, enriches
the circuitry in your brain

00:24:31.410 --> 00:24:34.460 align:middle line:10%
neurologically, but then
it produces a chemical

00:24:34.460 --> 00:24:36.750 align:middle line:10%
that's released in the
second brain, called

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:39.370 align:middle line:10%
the limbic brain or
the emotional brain.

00:24:39.370 --> 00:24:42.360 align:middle line:84%
So you can remember
your first kiss.

00:24:42.360 --> 00:24:45.110 align:middle line:84%
You could remember
graduating from college.

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:47.840 align:middle line:84%
You can remember the
birth of your first child.

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:50.280 align:middle line:84%
You can remember
finishing a marathon.

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:53.940 align:middle line:10%
You can remember catching a
fish off the coast of Mexico

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:56.850 align:middle line:10%
and then taking it home and
cooking it, and drinking

00:24:56.850 --> 00:24:59.130 align:middle line:10%
some really good wine
that tastes good,

00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:01.920 align:middle line:10%
and feeling the ocean
breeze on your face,

00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:03.790 align:middle line:10%
and seeing the sunset.

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:08.420 align:middle line:10%
And we could say that you were
